\section{Task2: Model Application to Famous Tracks and Self-designed Track}
We constructed the Power Distribution Model on the basis of Power Profile, the mechanism of MPA and Riding Drag Force Model in the previous section. In this section we will apply the theoretical model to practical circumstances.

\vspace{2ex}

First we use data from \textit{the 2021 Olympic Time Trial course in Tokyo, Japan} to verify.

The Tokyo's olympic games' men and women individual time trials use the same track, in which men need to race for a total of 44.2km in two laps, while women need to race for a total of 22.1km in one lap. The starting point and ending point are located in Fuji international racetrack. After leaving the racetrack, go clockwise through No. 151 Shizuoka County Road and then return to the racetrack. See \textit{Figure10} for terrain map:

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=12cm]{tokyo.png}
	\caption{Terrain Map for 2021 Tokyo Olympic Games}
\end{figure}

We divide men trial tracks into 12 pieces and women trial tracks into 6 pieces. Then we use methods and models mentioned in \textit{Section3} to test and verify whether the ideal shortest completion time in theory consists with the actual situation. At the same time the best optimal solution to apply power while traversing a certain trial course is extracted. Results are displayed in \textit{Table 3} below:

\begin{table}[H]
	\centering
	\caption{Tokyo Verification Results of Man}
		\begin{tabular}{lllll}
			\toprule
			& Men Sprinter & Men Time Trialist & Women Sprinter    & Women Time Trialist \\
			\midrule
			T/s   & 3413.6       & 3121.2            & 1740.6            & 1622.5              \\
			T/min & 56.89        & 52.02             & 29.01             & 27.04               \\
